paragraphs.text:
# What is Apache Kafka

> Apache Kafka is an open-source distributed event streaming platform used by thousands of companies for high-performance data pipelines, streaming analytics, data integration, and mission-critical applications.


## What is event streaming?

>Event streaming is the practice of capturing data in real-time from event sources like databases, sensors, mobile devices, cloud services, and software applications in the form of streams of events; storing these event >streams durably for later retrieval; manipulating, processing, and reacting to the event streams in real-time as well as retrospectively; and routing the event streams to different destination technologies as needed. Event >streaming thus ensures a continuous flow and interpretation of data so that the right information is at the right place, at the right time.

## In a nutshell...

Apache Kafka has three key capabilities:

* **To Publish**(produce) and **subscribe to**(consume) streams of records;
* **Store** streams of records in a **fault-tolerant** durable way into **topics**;
* **Process streams** of records as they occur.

paragraphs.text:
## How it’s used?

Kafka is generally used for two classes of applications:

* Building **real-time streaming data pipelines**;
* Building **real-time streaming applications**.

For example:

* Real-time analytics (e.g. fraud detection/e-commerce)
* Metrics collection and monitoring
* Log aggregation
* Ingesting data into other systems (e.g. Spark/Hadoop/Neo4j)
* Website activity tracking (page views, searches, or other actions users may take)

paragraphs.text: ## How it works? * It is a cluster of **brokers** * Brokers receive data from **producers** (many producers can send data concurrently) and keep it ready for **consumers** (many consumers can poll data at the same time) * To allow for parallelism, consumers are organized in **consumer groups** * It uses **Apache Zookeeper**, usally run in a cluster of servers called an **ensemble**, in order to: * Cluster management * Failure detection and recovery * More generally, to maintains configuration information * Produced data are "stored" in **topics**. The relation between producers and topics is N-to-N * Each topic can be splitted into **partitions** to increase the throughput and allow parallelism

msg.data:
How it works?

  • It is a cluster of brokers
  • Brokers receive data from producers (many producers can send data concurrently) and keep it ready for consumers (many consumers can poll data at the same time)
  • To allow for parallelism, consumers are organized in consumer groups
  • It uses Apache Zookeeper, usally run in a cluster of servers called an ensemble, in order to:
    • Cluster management
    • Failure detection and recovery
    • More generally, to maintains configuration information

  • Produced data are “stored” in topics. The relation between producers and topics is N-to-N
  • Each topic can be splitted into partitions to increase the throughput and allow parallelism

paragraphs.text:
### Topics

* A topic contains all messages of a given category
* Events in a topic are not deleted after consumption.
* Users defines for how long Kafka should retain the events (controlled by a per-topic configuration named **retention.ms**, which is 1 week by default)
* Records written to topics are persisted to disk and replicated to other servers for fault-tolerance. **replication-factor** is a topic level configuration (evaulated to 1 by default) and it is usally setted to 3. This means that there will always be three copies of your data. The replication is performed at the level of topic-partitions.

### Partition

* Kafka split topic in many partitions. This is controlled by a property configured at server level: **num.partitions**, which is 1 by default
* More partitions lead to higher throughput
